Articulating paper is the most reliable method to detect occlusal clearance of an onlay, as it visually marks high spots when the restoration is seated in occlusion. Depth cuts (A) are used during preparation, not verification, while visual inspection (B) is subjective and less precise. A wax chew-in (C) is useful for evaluating occlusal function but not for detecting fine occlusal interferences.
